---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import { generateBreadcrumbSchema } from '../lib/seo';

const title = 'Why Image Size Targets Are Best-Effort | LocalResizer';
const description = 'Understand why image size targets such as 20KB, 100KB, or 2MB are best-effort, what affects the result, and how the current LocalResizer tools handle that tradeoff.';
const breadcrumbItems = [
  { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
  { href: '/why-image-size-is-best-effort', label: 'Why target size is best-effort' },
];
const breadcrumbSchema = generateBreadcrumbSchema(breadcrumbItems);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} schemas={[breadcrumbSchema]}>
  <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbItems} />

  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-5 py-10 sm:py-14">
    <div class="text-center mb-10">
      <span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 rounded-full bg-amber-50 text-amber-700 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide uppercase mb-3">Support guide</span>
      <h1 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-stone-900 tracking-tight mb-4">Why image size targets are best-effort</h1>
      <p class="text-stone-500 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed">
        A page called “resize image to 20KB” sounds exact, but real images do not behave like a fixed spreadsheet cell. This guide explains why the current LocalResizer pages aim for a target budget rather than promising that every source file can land on the exact same byte count.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-7 shadow-soft border border-stone-100 mb-8 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-xl font-semibold text-stone-900">Why exact file size is hard in practice</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">
        File size is shaped by multiple variables at once: image dimensions, color complexity, transparency, fine detail, noise, compression format, and the compression level itself. Two photos with the same pixel dimensions can still compress to very different sizes because one might contain smooth backgrounds while the other contains hair, foliage, text, or shadows that are harder to compress cleanly.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">
        That is why a trustworthy tool should talk about moving <em>toward</em> a target budget rather than pretending every image can hit the same number exactly without tradeoffs. The current LocalResizer pages are built around that honest boundary: aim for the requested limit, keep the original file when it is already small enough, and avoid overpromising impossible precision.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-5 mb-8">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-6 shadow-soft border border-stone-100">
        <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-3">JPEG / WebP pages</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">
          These pages can adjust compression quality, which makes them more flexible for target-size work. Even then, the exact final number still depends on how compressible the source image is and how much visible quality loss is acceptable.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-6 shadow-soft border border-stone-100">
        <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-3">PNG pages</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">
          PNG behaves differently because it does not use the same lossy quality slider. If a PNG needs to become much smaller while staying PNG, the tool may need to reduce pixel dimensions instead of only tweaking compression strength.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-6 shadow-soft border border-stone-100">
        <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-3">Resize-to-size pages</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">
          These pages reduce dimensions first and can combine that with format-specific compression. They are still best-effort because different images respond differently even after the same size reduction strategy.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-7 shadow-soft border border-stone-100 mb-8">
      <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-4">What most affects whether you can hit 20KB, 100KB, or 2MB</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-stone-500 leading-relaxed list-disc pl-5">
        <li><strong>Image complexity:</strong> noisy photos, detailed textures, and text overlays compress less predictably than simple backgrounds or cleaner product photos.</li>
        <li><strong>Dimensions:</strong> large images carry more pixels, so size targets become harder unless the canvas can shrink.</li>
        <li><strong>Format:</strong> JPEG and WebP can trade quality for bytes more directly than PNG.</li>
        <li><strong>Transparency:</strong> PNG assets with transparency often need more careful handling than flat photos.</li>
        <li><strong>Target aggressiveness:</strong> the smaller the requested budget, the more likely visible tradeoffs or dimension changes become.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-7 shadow-soft border border-stone-100 mb-10 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-xl font-semibold text-stone-900">How to improve your chances of landing near the target</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">
        Start with the page that matches your real constraint. If the destination only has a file-size limit, use the compression or resize-by-size pages instead of an exact canvas page. If the image is already extremely large, try a less aggressive target first and work downward. If you are processing a PNG and exact PNG output is not mandatory, converting to a more compression-friendly format elsewhere may produce a smaller result.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">
        In other words, treat the target as a <strong>goal with boundaries</strong>, not as a magic guarantee. A good tool should help you make that tradeoff deliberately, and a good site should explain it before you hit the process button. That is exactly why this guide exists on LocalResizer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-5">
      <a href="/compress-image" class="no-underline bg-white rounded-2xl p-6 shadow-soft border border-stone-100 hover:border-teal-200 hover:bg-teal-50/40 transition-all">
        <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Compare compression pages</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">See how the current JPEG and PNG workflows differ before you choose a target-size page.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/resize-image" class="no-underline bg-white rounded-2xl p-6 shadow-soft border border-stone-100 hover:border-teal-200 hover:bg-teal-50/40 transition-all">
        <h2 class="font-[var(--font-heading)] text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Compare resize-by-size pages</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-stone-500 leading-relaxed">Review the current 20KB, 100KB, and 2MB pages when the real constraint is upload size rather than a fixed canvas.</p>
      </a>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
